column12: Etymology Note
Czech Republic proposal;Absolutno is a fictional miraculous substance in the sci-fi novel Továrna na absolutno (The Factory for the Absolute) by influential Czech writer Karel Čapek.
The name was originally Arabic: آخر النهر ʾāẖir an-nahr ('river's end').
first applied to η Cassiopeiae in the Skalnate Pleso Atlas of the Heavens published in 1950, but is not known prior to that.
the traditional name of the β Scorpii system has been rendered Akrab and Elakrab, derived (like Acrab) from Arabic: العقرب al-ʿaqrab ('the scorpion').
a modern contraction of the Bayer designation, coined in the 19th century, but which entered into common use only by the mid-20th century (< α Crucis)
The name was originally Arabic: الزبانى az-zubāná ('the claws').
Also called Aldhafera. The name is originally from Arabic: الضفيرة aḍ-ḍafīra ('the braid (or curl, or strand)' [of the lion's mane]).

The name is originally from Arabic: عذارى ʿaḏārá ('virgins'). In the Calendarium of Al Achsasi Al Mouakket, it is designated أول العذاري ʾawwil al-ʿaḏāriyy, translated into Latin as Prima Virginum ('first virgin').
The name was originally Arabic: الذيل aḏ-ḏayl (the train, lit. 'the tail').
The name is originally from Arabic: عين ʿayn ('eye') and was reviewed and adopted by the Working Group on Star Names.
From Arabic: عين الرامي ʿayn ar-rāmī ('eye of the archer')
The name is originally from Arabic: الأظفر al-ʾuẓfur ('the talons' [of the swooping eagle]), shared with μ Lyrae (Alathfar).
Cypriot proposal; Alasia is the first historically recorded name of Cyprus, dating back to mid-fifteenth century BC.

The name is originally from Arabic: البلدة al-balda ('town'). In the Calendarium of Al Achsasi Al Mouakket, it is designated نير البلدة nayyir al-baldah, translated into Latin as Lucida Oppidi ('brightest of the town')
The name is originally from Arabic: البالع al-bāliʿ ('the swallower').
The source of the name Albireo is not entirely clear.
From Arabic: الخباء al-ẖibāʾ ('tent'). In the Calendarium of Al Achsasi Al Mouakket, it is designated المنخر الغراب al-manẖar al-ġurāb, translated into Latin as Rostrum Corvi ('beak of the crow').
From Arabic: الخوار al‑ẖawwār ('the faint one').
Member of the Pleiades open star cluster (M45). Alcyone (Ancient Greek: Ἀλκυόνη Alkuonē) was one of the Pleiades sisters in Greek mythology.
The name was originally Arabic: الدبران ad-dabarān ('the follower' [of the Pleiades])
From Arabic: الذراع اليمين aḏ-ḏirāʿ al-yamīn ('the right arm' [of Cepheus]).
The name was originally الذنب aḏ-ḏanab ('the tail' [of the constellation of the Southern Fish]).
From Arabic: الضباع aḍ-ḍibāʿ ('the hyenas').
Shortening of Arabic: ذنب الدلفين ḏanab ad-dulfīn ('tail of the dolphin').
From Arabic: الفرق al-firq ('the flock'). Name given by Ulugh Beg to the asterism consisting of α, β and η Cephei.
From Arabic: الجدي al-jady ('the (male) kid'). Alternative traditional names are Al Giedi, Secunda Giedi and Algiedi Secunda.
From Arabic: الجانب al-jānib ('the flank'). Algenib is also another name for α Persei (Mirfak).
From Arabic: الجبهة al-jabha ('the forehead' [of the lion]).
From Arabic: الجانب al-jānib ('the flank'). Algenib is also another name for α Persei (Mirfak).
The traditional name Algorab is derived from Arabic: الغراب al-ġurāb ('the crow').
Derived from Arabic: الهنعة al-hanʿa ('the brand' [on the neck of the camel]).
The traditional name Alioth comes from the Arabic alyat al-hamal ("the sheep's fat tail").
From Arabic: (النسر) الطائر (an-nasr) aṭ-ṭāʾir ('the flying' [eagle]).
Nigerian proposal; Amadioha is the god of thunder in Igbo mythology. As well as representing justice, Amadioha is also a god of love, peace and unity.
Philippines proposal. Aman Sinaya is one of the two trinity deities of the Philippine's Tagalog mythology, and is the primordial deity of the ocean and protector of fisherman.
Turkish proposal; Anadolu is the primary homeland of Turkey and refers to the motherland in Turkish culture.
Swedish proposal; Aniara is the name of a spaceship in the epic poem Aniara by Swedish author Harry Martinson.

Andorran proposal; Arcalis is a famous peak in the north of Andorra, where the Sun passes through a hole in the mountain twice a year at fixed dates. It was used as a primitive solar calendar and reference point for shepherds and early inhabitants of Andorra.

The Greek term Ἀρκτοῦρος means "The Guard"; it was used for this star by all ancient astronomers (Eratosthenes, Hipparchus, Ptolemy) and is possibly an Egyptian reminiscence because it formed part of the Egyptian constellation of the Hippo Goddess who guarded the constellation of the Bull's Leg (or Bull's Thigh) seen in UMa. cf. Hesiod, Works and Days 566
ascella ("armpit"). Source: Almagest 1515
Togolese proposal; Atakoraka means the chain of the Atacora: the largest mountain range in Togo.
Contraction of Bayer designation A(lpha) Tri(anguli) A(ustralis).
Invented for The Air Almanac of the HM Nautical Almanac Office
Mexican proposal. Axólotl means water animal in the native Nahuatl language, which is a unique and culturally significant endemic amphibious species from the basin of Mexico.
Myanmar proposal; Ayeyarwady is the largest and most important river in Myanmar.
South Korean proposal; Baekdu is the highest mountain on the Korean peninsula, situated in North Korea, and symbolises the national spirit of Korea.
Almagest 1515
Senegalese proposal; Belel is a rare source of water in the north of Senegal.

Ukrainian proposal. Berehynia was a Slavic deity of waters and riverbanks but in more recent times her status has been promoted to that of a national goddess — "hearth mother, protectress of the earth".
Indian proposal; Bibhā [/bɪbɦa/] is the Bengali pronunciation of the Sanskrit word Vibha, which means a bright beam of light.
Bosnia and Herzegovina proposal; Bosona is the name given to the territory of Bosnia in the 10th century. Later, the name was transformed to Bosnia originating from the name of the Bosna river.
Australian proposal; Bubup is the Boonwurrung word for child.
Ethiopian proposal; Buna is the commonly used word for coffee in Ethiopia.
French proposal; Bélénos was the god of light, of the Sun, and of health in Gaulish mythology.
Uruguayan proposal; Ceibo is the name of the native tree of Uruguay that gives rise to the national flower.
Miguel de Cervantes Saavedra (1547-1616) was a famous Spanish writer and author of "El Ingenioso Hidalgo Don Quixote de la Mancha".
Chalawan is a mythological crocodile king from a Thai folktale.
Thai proposal; Chao Phraya is the great river of Thailand.
Slovakian proposal; Chasoň is an ancient Slovak term for Sun.
Chechia is a flat-surfaced, traditional red wool hat worn by men and women, symbolising the country's rich traditions and is considered as the national headdress for in Tunisia.

Haitian proposal; The Citadelle is a large mountaintop fortress in Nord, Haiti built after Haiti's independence, and was designated a UNESCO World Heritage site along with the nearby Sans-Souci Palace.
El Salvadorian proposal; Citalá means River of stars in the native Nahuat language.
Nicaraguan proposal; Cocibolca is the Nahualt name for the largest lake in Central America in Nicaragua.
Nicolaus Copernicus or Mikolaj Kopernik (1473-1543) was a Polish astronomer who proposed the heliocentric model of the solar system in his book "De revolutionibus orbium coelestium".
Lamb (1673), Piazzi (1814)
Trinidad and Tobago proposal; Dingolay means to dance, twist and turn in elaborate movements, symbolising the culture and language of the ancestors of the people of Trinidad and Tobago.
Mauritian proposal; Diya is an oil lamp that is brought by Indian ancestors to Mauritius in the 1820's, and is used for lighting during special occasions, including the light festival of Diwali.
Indonesian proposal; Dofida means our star in Nias language.

Russian proposal; Dombay is a resort region in the North Caucasus mountains that is enclosed by mountain forests and rich wildlife, including bears (as this star lies in the constellation Ursa Major, the great bear).
Costa Rican proposal; Dìwö in Bribri language means the sun (bigger than the sun we know) and that never turns off.
Syrian proposal; Ebla was one of the earliest kingdoms in Syria, and served as a prominent region in the 2nd and 3rd millenia B.C.
Mozambique proposal; Emiw represents love in the local Makhuwa language of the northern region of Mozambique.
Fafnir was a Norse mythological dwarf who turned into a dragon.

Cuban proposal; Felix Varela (1788–1853) was the first to teach science in Cuba at the San Carlos and San Ambrosio Seminary. He opened the way to education for all, and began the experimental teaching of physics in Cuba.

Italian proposal. Flegetonte is the underworld river of fire from Greek Mythology in the Italian narrative poem on the afterlife "Divina Commedia" (Divine Commedy) by Dante Alighieri, chosen as an allusion to the star's fiery nature.
The name is originally from Arabic: فم الحوت fum al-ḥawt ('mouth of the fish'). In Persian astrology, this star was called "Haftorang, Watcher of the South", one of the royal stars.
Chinese Taipei proposal; Formosa is the historical name of Taiwan used in the 17th century, meaning beautiful in Latin.
Austrian proposal; Franz is a character in the movie "Sissi" embodying an emperor of Austria in the XIXth century. The role is played by the actor Karlheinz Böhm.
Icelandic proposal; Funi is an old Icelandic word meaning fire or blaze.
Bhutan proposal; Gakyid means happiness. Gross National Happiness is the development philosophy conceived and followed in Bhutan and is one of Bhutan's contributions to the world.
British proposal; In Manx Gaelic, Gloas means to shine (like a star).
Brunei proposal; Gumala is a Malay word, which means a magic bezoar stone found in snakes, dragons, etc.
Helvetios is the Latin for "the Helvetian" and refers to the Celtic tribe that lived in Switzerland during the Middle Ages.
Algerian proposal; Hoggar is the name of the main mountain range in the Sahara Desert in southern Algeria.
Finnish proposal; Horna is hell or the underworld from Finnic mythology.
Honduran proposal; Hunahpú was one of the twin gods who became the Sun in K'iche' (Quiché) Mayan mythology as recounted in the Popol Vuh.
Hungarian proposal; Hunor was a legendary ancestor of the Huns and the Hungarian nation, and brother of Magor.
Albanian proposal; Historians largely believe that the Albanians are descendants of the Illyrians, a term Albanians proudly call themselves.
Peruvian proposal; Inquill was one half of the couple involved in the tragic love story Way to the Sun by famous Peruvian writer Abraham Valdelomar.
Malaysian proposal; Intan means diamond in the Malay language (Bahasa Melayu), alluding to the shining of a star.
Intercrus means "between the legs" in Latin style, referring to the star's position in the constellation Ursa Major.
Slovenian proposal; Irena is a leading character in the novel Under the Free Sun: a Story of the Ancient Grandfathers by Slovene writer Fran Saleški Finžgar. Irena is a woman of the court.
Gabonese proposal; Itonda, in the Myene tongue, corresponds to all that is beautiful.
Kenyan proposal; The word Kalausi means a very strong whirling column of wind in the Dholuo language of Kenya.
Japanese proposal; Kamuy is a word in the Ainu language denoting a supernatural entity possessing spiritual energy.
New Zealand proposal; Karaka is the word in the Māori language for a plant endemic to New Zealand that produces a bright orange, fleshy fruit.
Iranian proposal; Kaveh is one of the heroes of Shahnameh, the epic poem composed by Persian poet Ferdowsi between 977 and 1010 CE. Kaveh is a blacksmith who symbolises justice.
Puerto Rican proposal; Koeia was the word for star in the language of the Taíno Indigenous People of the Caribbean.
Estonian proposal; Koit is Estonian for the time when the Sun rises in the morning (dawn).
Greek proposal; Lerna was the name of a lake in the eastern Peloponnese, where the Lernaean Hydra, an immortal mythical nine-headed beast lived. The star lies in the constellation of Hydra.

Libertas is Latin for "liberty". Liberty refers to social and political freedoms, and a reminder that there are people derived of liberty in the world even today. The constellation Aquila represents an eagle - a popular symbol of liberty.
Lich is a fictional undead creature known for controlling other undead creatures with magic.
Latvian proposal; Liesma means flame, and it is the name of a character from the Latvian poem Staburags un Liesma.
Nicolas-Louis de Lacaille in 1757
Hong Kong proposal; Lion Rock is a lion-shaped peak overlooking Hong Kong and is a cultural symbol with deep respect from the local community.
Luxembourger proposal; The Lucilinburhuc fortress was built in 963 by the founder of Luxembourg, Count Siegfried.
Portuguese proposal; Lusitânia is the ancient name of the western region of the Iberic Peninsula where the Lusitanian people lived and where most of modern-day Portugal is situated.

Colombian proposal; Macondo is the mythical village of the novel One Hundred Years of Solitude (Cien años de soledad) the classic novel by Gabriel García Marquez. Macondo is a fictional place where magic and reality are mixed.
German proposal; Mago is a National Park in Ethiopia noted for its giraffes. The star also happens to be in the constellation of Camelopardis (the giraffe).

Azerbaijani proposal; Mahsati Ganjavi (1089–1159) is one of the brightest shining stars of Azerbaijani poetry. She was said to have associated with both Omar Khayyam and Nizami and was well educated and talented and played numerous musical instruments.

Aruban proposal; Malmok is an indigenous name given to a beach in Aruba with a narrow sandy stretch that interrupts the limestone and rocky terrace along the coast. Its shallow clear Caribbean waters make it a popular snorkelling spot.

Mongolian proposal; Mazaalai is the Mongolian name for the endangered Gobi bear subspecies (Ursus arctos gobiensis) of the Gobi Desert region of Mongolia, and the name of the first Mongolian satellite.
Romanian proposal; Moldoveanu is the highest peak in Romania of the Făgăraș mountain range with an altitude of 2544 metres.
Panamanian proposal; Montuno is the traditional costume the man wears in the “El Punto”, a Panamanian dance in which a man and woman dance to the sound of drums.
Serbian proposal; Morava is the longest river system in Serbia.
Palestinian proposal; Moriah is an ancient name for the mountain within the Old City of Jerusalem.
Burkina Faso proposal; Mouhoun, also called Volta Noire, is the largest river in Burkina Faso and plays an important role in the lives of the people in the areas it passes through.
Tanzanian proposal; Mpingo is a famous tree that grows in southern Tanzania and produces ebony wood used for musical instruments and curios.
Bayer (1603) "in naso, barbaris muscida." - attributed to "Barbarians"
Latin for 'music' (the ancient Greek musician Arion's life was saved at sea by dolphins (delphinus) after attracting their attention by playing his kithara)
Danish proposal; Muspelheim is the Norse mythological realm of fire. The first gods used the sparks of Muspelheim to form the sun, moon, planets, and stars.

Dominican Republic proposal; Márohu the god of drought is the protector of the Sun and is engraved at a higher position on the stalagmite than Boinayel in the El Puente cave, where the Sun makes its way down every 21 December.
Swiss proposal; Mönch is one of the prominent peaks of the Bernese Alps in Switzerland.

South African proposal; Naledi means star in the Sesotho, SeTswana and SePedi languages and is typically given as a name to girls in the hope that they will bring light, joy and peace to their communities.
Zambian proposal; Natasha means thank you in many languages of Zambia.
Bode (1801)
Ecuadorian proposal; Nenque means the Sun in the language spoken by the Indigenous Waorani tribes of the Amazon regions of Ecuador
Belgian proposal; Nervia, adapted from Nervii, was a prominent Belgian Celtic tribe.
Canadian proposal; Nikawiy is the word for mother in the Indigenous Cree language of Canada.
Argentinian proposal; Nosaxa means spring in the Moqoit language. The word comes from a combination of nosahuec, which means renew, and ñaaxa, which means year.
American proposal; Nushagak is a regional river near Dilingham, Alaska, which is famous for its wild salmon that sustain local Indigenous communities.
Ivory Coast proposal; Nyamien refers to the supreme creator deity of Akan mythology.
Norwegian proposal; means 'star' in the Sámi language.
Ogma was a deity of eloquence, writing, and great physical strength in the Celtic mythologies of Ireland and Scotland, and may be related to the Gallo-Roman deity "Ogmios".

Au-haele, Hōkū-‘ula and Paikauhale are documented as three stars in a line, running from north to south. Two of the most reliable sources—Mary Puku‘i and Ruby Johnson—both identify Hōkū-‘ula as Antares (α Sco), which makes Au-haele Alniyat (σ Sco) and Paikauhale τ Sco.
Singaporean proposal; Parumleo is a Latin term for little lion, symbolising Singapore's struggle for independence.
Invented for The Air Almanac of the HM Nautical Almanac Office
Jordanian proposal; Petra is a historical and archaeological city in southern Jordan and a UNESCO World Heritage site.
Lebanese proposal; Phoenicia was an ancient thalassocratic civilisation of the Mediterranean that originated from the area of modern-day Lebanon.
Chilean proposal; Pincoya is a female water spirit from southern Chilean mythology who is said to bring drowned sailors to the Caleuche so that they can live in the afterlife.

In Tahiti, a traditional story is told of a brother and sister, named Pipiri and Rehua, who flee their parents into the sky and become stars. Their parents call them Pipiri ma while chasing them into the sky: ma "with, and" is used after names to mean "et al." In one account, the children become Shaula and Lesath in the tip of the tail of Scorpio, and in another they become Mu² and Mu¹ Scorpii.[citation needed] (In a similar version of the story told in the Cook Islands, they become Omega¹ and Omega² Scorpii).
Liechtenstein proposal; In the local dialect of Triesenberg, Pipoltr is a bright and visible butterfly, alluding to the properties of a star.
Cook Islands proposal; Poerava is the word in the Cook Islands Maori language for a large mystical black pearl of utter beauty and perfection.
Ran is the Norse goddess of the sea, who stirs up the waves and captures sailors with her net.
Malagasy proposal; Rapeto is a giant creature from Malagasy tales.
Spanish proposal; Rosalia de Castro was a significant figure of Galician culture and prominent Spanish writer, whose pioneeting work often referenced the night and celestial objects.
< Venator reversed (Niccolo Cacciatore > Nicolaus Venator, responsible for 1814 star catalogue)
Nepalese proposal; Sagarmatha is the Nepali name for the highest peak in the world (also known as Mount Everest) and symbol of national pride of Nepal.
Traditional name from Arabic: سیف الجبار sayf al-jabbār, literally 'saif ('sword') of the giant'.
Maltese proposal; Sansuna is the name of the mythological giant from traditional Maltese folk tales that carried the stones of the Gozo megalithic temples on her head.
from the obsolete constellation of Sceptrum Brandenburgicum
Pakistani proposal; Shama is an Urdu literary term meaning a small lamp or flame, symbolic of the light of the star.

United Arab Emirates proposal; Sharjah is the cultural capital of United Arab Emirates, and considered the city of knowledge due to its many educational centers, institutes, museums, libraries and heritage centers.
Ghanaian proposal; means 'gold' in the Ewe language.
Polish proposal; named after Solaris, a novel by Stanisław Lem.
The Latin term is a translation of the Greek στάχυς which is a translation of Akkadian shubultu [literally written shu-bu-ul-tu4], all meaning: ear of grain.
Dutch proposal; named after The Starry Night by Vincent van Gogh.
Croatian proposal; named after Stribog, the god of winds in Slavic mythology. Stribor is also a character in the book Priče iz davnine (Croatian Tales of Long Ago) by Ivana Brlić-Mažuranić.
< Nicolaus reversed (Niccolo Cacciatore > Nicolaus Venator, responsible for 1814 star catalogue)
Sri Lankan proposal; Sāmaya means peace in the Sinhalese language.
Lithuanian proposal; Taika means peace in the Lithuanian language.
Bulgarian proposal; Tangra is the supreme celestial god that early Bulgars worshiped.
Bolivian proposal; Tapecue means eternal path in Guarani and represents the Milky Way through which the first inhabitants of the Earth arrived and could return.
Israeli proposal; Tevel means Universe or everything and begins with the letter Taf, the last letter in the Hebrew alphabet.
Bangladeshi proposal; Timir means darkness in Bengali language, alluding to the star being far away in the darkness of space.

Moroccan proposal; Tislit is the name of a lake in the Atlas mountains of Morocco. It means the bride in the Amazigh language and it is associated with a heartbroken beautiful girl in an ancient local legend.

Titawin (also known as Medina of Tetouan) is a settlement in northern Morocco and UNESCO World Heritage Site. Historically it was an important point of contact between two civilizations (Spanish and Arab) and two continents (Europe and Africa) after the 8th century.
Tojil is the name of one of the Mayan deities related to rain, storms, and fire.
Tonatiuh was the Aztec god of the Sun.
Irish proposal. Tuiren was the aunt of the hunterwarrior Fionn mac Cumhaill of Irish legend, who was turned into a hound by the jealous fairy Uchtdealbh.
Brazilian proposal; Tupi is the name of the most populous Indigenous People living on the eastern coast of South America, before the Portuguese arrived in the 16th century.
Paraguayan proposal; Tupã is one of four principle gods of the Guarani Cosmogony in popular Paraguayan folklore that helped the supreme god Ñamandu to create the Universe.
Pitcairn Islands proposal. Uklun means us or we in the Pitkern language of the people of Pitcairn Islands.
Iraqi proposal; Uruk was an ancient city of the Sumer and Babylonian civilizations in Mesopotamia situated along an ancient channel of the Euphrates river in modern-day Iraq.
From the latin "Veritas", truth. The ablative form means "where there is truth".
Nanjing proposal; Xihe (羲和) is the goddess of the sun in the Chinese mythology and also represents the earliest astronomers and developers of calendars in ancient China.
